XPS measurements were carried out to further reveal the valence state of elements and chemical environment of TWC3 (Fig. 3
                        ). All the spectra have been calibrated with C1s to 284.8 eV. The XPS survey spectra indicates that the W, Ti, and O are the main elements of TWC3 (Fig. 3a), with the atomic ratio of approximate 0.24%, 32.9%, and 66.8%, respectively (the ratio of C is excluded due to the carbon contamination). The binding energies of Ti 2p3/2 and Ti 2p1/2 for pure TiO2 are 458.9 and 464.6 eV, respectively, which correspond to the TiO2 anatase phase [27]. Whereas the binding energies of Ti 2p3/2 and Ti 2p1/2 for TWC3 are 459.0 and 464.7 eV, respectively. The shifts toward high energy level can be ascribed to the interference of TiO2 energy level by W6+ 
                        [16]. Similarly, the binding energies of W 4f7/2 and W 4f5/2 for TW2 shifted toward the low energy level when compared with pure WO3, which also confirms the formation of a stable structure of W-O-Ti bonds [28]. The O 1s signals at 530.2 eV and 532.2 eV correspond to the oxygen of the TiO2 lattice and hydroxyl groups, respectively (Fig. 3d). The hydroxyl groups may be due to the adsorption of water on the sample [27]. With the introduction of WO3 and CQDs, the binding energy of O continues to decrease in addition to hydroxyl oxygen. As shown in Fig. 3e, the main peak at 284.8 eV is attributed to the sp2 C–C bond. The other two peaks at 286.5 eV and 289.0 eV belong to the C-O-C bond and CO bond, respectively [19,26]. Furthermore, the addition of CQDs shifted the binding energies of Ti, W, and O elements to varying degrees, which also proves that CQDs, TiO2 and WO3 are well combined, and the TiO2/WO3/CQDs was successfully synthesized.
